===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|en|enm|perche}}, from {{der|en|fro|perche}}, from {{der|en|la|pertica||staff”, “long pole”, “measuring rod}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|es|perch}}

# a [[rod]], [[staff]], or [[branch]] of a [[tree]] etc used as a [[roost]] by a [[bird]]
#* Tennyson
#*: Not making his high place the lawless '''perch''' / Of winged ambitions.
# a [[pole]] connecting the fore gear and hind gear of a [[spring carriage]]; a [[reach]].
# {{lb|en|figurative}} a [[position]] that is [[secure]] and [[advantageous]], especially one which is [[prominent]] or [[elevated]]
# {{lb|en|figurative}} a position that is overly elevated or {{l|en|haughty}}
#* {{quote-book|author={{w|John Webster}}|year=1613|title=The Duchess of Malfi|section=II, iv|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Duchess_of_Malfi/Act_II,_scene_iv}}
#*: {{quote|en|You may thank me, lady:<br/>I have taken you off your melancholy perch,<br/>Bore you upon my fist, and show'd you game,<br/>And let you fly at it.<br/>I pray thee kiss me.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} a [[linear]] [[measure]] of 5½ [[yard]]s, equal to a [[rod]], a [[pole]] or ¼ [[chain]]; the related [[square]] measure
# a [[cubic]] measure of [[stonework]] [[equal]] to 16.6 × 1.5 × 1 [[feet]]
# {{lb|en|textiles}} a [[frame]] used to [[examine]] [[cloth]]
# a [[bar]] used to support a [[candle]] (especially in a church)

